| Feature           | Short Polling                     | Long Polling                        |
| ----------------- | --------------------------------- | ----------------------------------- |
| Request Frequency | Fixed interval (e.g., every 5s)   | One request stays open until update |
| Network Load      | High (many requests, often empty) | Lower (fewer requests overall)      |
| Latency           | Mediumâ€“High (depends on interval) | Low (server responds immediately)   |
| Complexity        | Very simple                       | Moderate                            |
| Best For          | Non-critical updates              | Near real-time apps (chat, scores)  |


ğŸ”¹ Why Short polling for crickBuzz ?

Short Polling â†’ Client requests server at fixed intervals (e.g., every 5s).
âœ… Simple, CDN-friendly, works everywhere.
âŒ Wastes bandwidth, not true real-time.

Long Polling â†’ Client request stays open until server has new data.
âœ… Near real-time, fewer empty responses.
âŒ Higher server resource usage, harder to scale, less CDN support.

ğŸ‘‰ For apps like Cricbuzz, short polling is often chosen because itâ€™s simpler, scalable, and â€œgood enoughâ€ (3â€“5s delay), while WebSockets are used when sub-second latency is required.